com.habelitz.jsobjectizer.jsom.api.expression
Interface StaticArrayCreator

All Superinterfaces:
Expression, JSOM, PrimaryExpression
public interface StaticArrayCreator
extends PrimaryExpression

This PrimaryExpression type represents a new expression for creating static arrays.

This class handles the creators for both static arrays of primitive types and static arrays of Object types. The method isArrayOfPrimitiveType can be used to find out which variant is represented by an instance of this class.

Furthermore the behavior of some methods depends on if an instance of this class represents an array creator with an explicitly stated initializer like 

      new AnyType[][] { {initializer, ...}, {initializer, ...}}
or like 
      new AnyType[expression][expression]
      new AnyType[expression][][][]
what can be found out easily by calling the method hasExplicitInitializer().

Author:
Dieter Habelitz
See Also:
for new expressions that instantiate objects via a constructor call.

getArrayInitializers

java.util.List<VariableInitializer> getArrayInitializers()
If this represents an array creator with an explicit initializer this method returns a list of the array initializers.

Calling this method equals an getArrayInitializers(null) call.

Returns:
A list of the array initializers. If 'hasExplicitInitializer() != true' or if 'hasExplicitInitializer() == true' but the initializer is an empty initializer null will be returned.
See Also:
getArrayInitializers(List), getArraySizeDeclarators()

getArrayInitializers

java.util.List<VariableInitializer> getArrayInitializers(java.util.List<VariableInitializer> pList)
If this represents an array creator with an explicit initializer this method returns a list of the array initializers.

Parameters:
pList - If this argument isn't null the array initializers will be added to this list and this list object will be returned. Otherwise a new list will be created for the result.
Returns:
A list of the array initializers. If 'hasExplicitInitializer() != true' or if 'hasExplicitInitializer() == true' but the initializer is an empty initializer null will be returned, even if the argument pList isn't null.

getNumberOfArrayDeclarators

int getNumberOfArrayDeclarators()
Returns the number of array declarators, i.e. the number of [] character sequences.

The interpretation of this method's result depends on if this represents an array creator with an explicit initializer or not. For the three formal examples given within this class' head documentation this method would return the values 2, 0 and 3 respectively.

Returns:
The number of array declarators.

getPrimitiveType

Returns:
The type of the array elements or null if 'isArrayOfPrimitiveType() == false'.

getQualifiedTypeIdentifier

java.util.List<ComplexTypeIdentifier> getQualifiedTypeIdentifier(java.util.List<ComplexTypeIdentifier> pList)
If this represents a creator of a static array of objects this method returns a list of the type (which may be a qualified type) of the array elements.

Parameters:
pList - If this argument isn't null the array element type will be added to this list and this list object will be returned. Otherwise a new list will be created for the result. For a qualified type the most left identifier is the first list entry and the actual array element type the last one.
Returns:
A list containing the (qualified) type of the array elements. If if 'isArrayOfPrimitiveType() == true' null will be returned, even if the argument pList isn't null.
See Also:
getPrimitiveType()
